properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, will begin early Friday morning. Rain will begin overnight tonight and continue through Friday night, with the most rainfall occurring Friday afternoon and evening. Rainfall amounts of 30 to 50 mm are expected, with higher amounts possible in embedded thunderstorms. Highest rainfall amounts are expected north of Lake Superior between Nipigon and Marathon, including Pays Plat, Terrace Bay and Neys. A Rainfall Warning may be required. Environment Canada meteorologists are continuing to monitor the situation closely. A deepening Colorado low moving into Northwestern Ontario is responsible for the rain and snow in Northern Ontario today into the weekend. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An extreme winter storm will pummel parts of southern Manitoba over the next couple of days. An approaching Colorado low will continue to bring heavy wet snow to southern Manitoba tonight. Further snowfall amounts will be 5 to 15 cm by morning, on top of the snow that fell during the day on Thursday. The most intense winter storm conditions are expected for Friday and Friday night as the Colorado low draws closer and intensifies. The western half of the Red River Valley may be hit with an extraordinary amount of snow. Snowfall amounts for Friday and Friday night could exceed 50 cm particularly towards the Manitoba escarpment. Areas closer to the Red River, including the City of Winnipeg, could get between 10 and 25 cm of wet snow. Very strong winds will accompany this heavy snow on Friday. Gusts of 70 to 80 km/h are forecast throughout southern Manitoba, and gusts over 100 km/h are possible off the Manitoba Lakes. Travelling will become difficult if not impossible as the day wears on, with heavy, accumulating snow, strong winds and temperatures near zero resulting in treacherous conditions. The combination of heavy, wet snow and strong winds will likely result in downed trees and power lines. The area of extreme snowfall will shift northward and westward Friday night and into Saturday. It will affect a broad area through Westman and parts of the Interlake. This storm system will weaken through the day on Saturday. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-11T19:00:56-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain and strong winds beginning this evening and continuing into Saturday... Rain will move into southwestern Nova Scotia late this afternoon and continue eastward overnight to reach Cape Breton by Saturday morning. Total rainfall amounts of 20 to 40 mm are expected for much of Nova Scotia by Saturday evening, with some areas along the Atlantic coast possibly reaching or exceeding 50 mm. Along with the rain, strong easterly winds will also increase during the day today in the southwest and spread overnight into eastern Nova Scotia by Saturday morning. Gusts may reach 80 km/h along exposed areas of the Atlantic coast. Rough and pounding surf will also impact parts of the Atlantic coast beginning this afternoon and diminish by Saturday evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: An extreme winter storm will continue to pummel parts of southern Manitoba over the next couple of days. The most intense winter storm conditions are expected for today and tonight for the Red River Valley as a Colorado low draws closer and intensifies. The western half of the Red River Valley may be hit with an extraordinary amount of snow. Snowfall amounts for today and Friday night could exceed 50 cm particularly towards the Manitoba escarpment. Areas closer to the Red River, including the City of Winnipeg, could get between 10 and 25 cm of wet snow mixed with ice pellets. Very strong winds will accompany this heavy snow as well. Gusts of 70 to 80 km/h are forecast throughout southern Manitoba, and gusts over 100 km/h are possible off the Manitoba Lakes or in wind prone areas around the Riding Mountains. Travelling will become difficult if not impossible as the day wears on, with heavy, accumulating snow, strong winds and temperatures near zero resulting in treacherous conditions. The combination of heavy, wet snow and strong winds will likely result in downed trees and power lines. The area of extreme snowfall will shift northward and westward tonight into Saturday and begin affecting a broader area through Westman and parts of the Interlake. This storm system will gradually weaken through the day on Saturday. ### Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Significant snowfall, freezing rain and ice pellets will continue today. A northeast to southwest stationary front is positioned over Far-Northwestern Ontario. Areas near the Manitoba border are expected to get additional snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm today. Near the front, an extended period of freezing rain and ice pellets is possible. Rain will continue in areas east of the front. The wintry mix of precipitation is forecast to change over to rain this evening. ### Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 20 cm is expected. A Pacific low pressure system over southwestern Yukon this morning will give snow to Old Crow today resulting in total accumulations of 15 to 20 cm. The snow will end this evening as the low moves out of the territory. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Along with a wintery mix of precipitation, severe wind gusts to 100 km/h are expected along the shore of Lake Winnipeg today. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, continues. The ground, already near saturation, has little ability to absorb further rainfall. Rain (or at times wet snow) will continue in southeastern Manitoba today. Bands of precipitation will continue to move through the area today and a further 5 to 15 mm should be expected. Locally higher amounts are also possible as isolated thunderstorms move through the area. Recent heavy rains in southeastern Manitoba have resulted in saturated ground and localized flooding, which will be made worse with the current storm system. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
